@terceiro previous code was running 3 significantly heavy queries: the first query did string matching + distinct() + count() just to get the count of tests. The second query (again with string matching) was ordering tests by number of failures/xfails/skips/passes, the result of this second query was just to build a dynamic [filter](https://github.com/Linaro/squad/blob/master/squad/frontend/tests.py#L119) for the third query that generates content for the test results page, which used suite_id and test name to query tests. Although test name is indexed, this would still take some time process.

All that was replaced by 2 much lighter queries: first one that does string matching and return all tests for a build. All previous calculations are made in memory: pagination, ordering and selection of the tests to be displayed. The second query simply passes the wanted tests ids.

Running these changes locally for an android-lkft project, it lowered loading times from 4000ms to just a couple of 100ms. Also, we are already doing something similar for workers, when loading tests to generate regressions and fixes.

