We can use any Iterable type which contains the required elements.   We could manually create a HashSet, but as the method we are passing it to isn't actually  using the Set<> API this would simply be an expensive conversion without much benefit.  It is true the converting to a HashSet would allow the Iterable to cast to a Set at some future point, though I don't think may Java code would expect this to work.

```
   void foo(Iterable i)
   {
      Set set = (Set) i;
      ...
    }
```

Technically we should be wrapping to an unmodifiableSet using Collections as the Iterable since it cannot be modified currently.   I haven't tested what happens if we modified the list, though as it is backed by a Object[] it should cause an error as expected.

Long term, we won't actually convert anything here.   Once the reverse bridge is complete we can just pass Python sets to the converter to get a python.lang.PySet instance which implements Set<> and Iterable<> so problem solved.

