Yes. It is definitely intentional. We don't need to signal all state changes. There are only certain events in specific situations where we need to signal to the next layer.
   
The `SignalAnyStateChange` mechanism is used to make sure we signal the changes and invoke the `Connection` related callback *at the end and after processing and making all changes*. This is very important or else we can create code re-entry issues. There are comments in the code in couple places (`HandleReceive()` or `SendMessage()`) which try to clarify and emphasize this:
```c++
    // Signal any state changes. This is done at the very end when the
    // `SendMessage()` is fully processed (all state and local
    // variables are updated) to ensure that we do not have any
    // reentrancy issues (e.g., if the callback signalling state
    // change triggers another tx).

    SignalAnyStateChange();
```

