@prutskov, @vnlitvinov , and I thought it was more confusing to have `list_of_blocks` for non-full-axis virtual partitions, and a separate accessor like `block` or `data` for block partitions. non-full-axis virtual partitions and block partitions are also supposed to expose the same API.

In the long term, I want to consolidate the block and virtual partitions into a single class for each engine and remove the `full_axis` param from the axis partition constructor. We would always use the `num_splits` argument to `apply` explicitly to specify the number of splits. That will reduce code duplication and prevent bugs like the many we've had from not treating non-full-axis virtual partitions the same as full-axis virtual partitions, e.g. #4691, #4692, #4676, #4464. Using a common `list_of_blocks` for both partition class takes us toward that goal.

One alternative was to make all partition classes have a block accessor like `data()` that forces materialization of virtual partitions with multiple blocks, but this didn't seem necessary for any existing use case, and it seemed better to combine the blocks within the remote `apply` call for cases like binary operations, where we [use all the blocks](https://github.com/modin-project/modin/blob/eee5f435f68786778184c4886ff25d386fce0c4f/modin/core/dataframe/pandas/partitioning/partition_manager.py#L1288).

